comments.text: I'm a taxidermist and when I first started a few years ago I would look for raccoon and possum bones and whatnot in the woods near train tracks, so with the bones mentioned here, I'd be curious to know more about what the "bleaching" described. If the bones were corroded and the bone was flaking, you could easily say it has been bleached by human beings. But, there are natural decomposition circumstances in which a bone could end up whitened. It's very very common in places with heavy rain, and it's very common for bones found from the same animal to be not only scattered around by wildlife, and the bigger the deceased animal the bigger the scattering of the bones because the predator or scavenger is likely much bigger, and also, when bones are scattered like this early in decomposition a bone under a tree found in mud could very likely have more remaining flesh or grease (yellow/brown color) that bones found on rock or in the sun not protected as much from the rain. Also, often when someone drowns in water it's common for feet still in shoes to be found downstream because decomposition in water weakens certain joints much faster than the rest of the body so during decomposition feet will often detach in those circumstances. I hope I don't sound crazy, I'm just a taxidermist, I mean no disrespect to these girls. I do think it's very possible they got scared by something and ran off, separating them from the dog, but from what I know of decomposition I think in the end, one girl drowned, the other took photos so search parties might be able to figure it out, and then the other died of the elements, and maybe scavenging wildlife scattered the remains post mortem.

Regarding the bone bleaching, well the bag was supposedly found near a rice paddy and the rest of the remains of the two girls were close to farmland if I am not mistaken, along a river. So it could possibly be the result of chemical run off from fertilisers, which would bleach the bones in a short amount of time, such as a week or two. Phosphorus, which was supposedly found to have contaminated Kris's hip bone is also a major component of crop fertilisers. Nitrogen, Phospohorus and Potassium are the 3 integral elements to plant/crop fertiliser and requirements for all organic plant life. Sometimes farmers treat their crops specifically with just one of those 3 compounds, if the crops are showing deficiencies of say just one of the compounds. 


This is not uncommon at all, although I would be shocked if this was the case in the middle of the jungle, where extensive farming is not common at all. But perhaps the fertiliser or chemicals had been dumped further up stream, contaminating the water, and leaking further down stream. I have heard many stories about waterways becoming contaminated due to chemical run-off from crop fertilisers. That would have the potential to bleach anything organic that it came into contact with. But for that to happen in the Panama jungle, with barely any farms or people around, is almost unheard of and super strange. So it still doesn't add up. 


Really a large research team of say 50 people need to go in together, transversing the entire route they supposedly took, right up to this little remote village and check everything out thoroughly. Including any farming and crop irrigation going on. Test some samples of water where the bones were found as well. That's the only way to know for sure. That's never going to happen though.

comments.text: In another video, the parents of Kris Kremers took the same trail to get an idea of the terrain the young women faced months earlier. They stated that there could have been no way for the ladies to have gotten lost because thick vegetation surrounds the trail on both sides. However, I think they did not factor in the following: 1) They retraced their daughter's steps already knowing the outcome. Hindsight is always viewed with 20/20 glasses; 2) The parents had guides with them and could have never gotten lost, whereas Kris and Lisanne were unguided and unfamiliar with the area; 3) Having hiked countless trails in many countries (including tropical ones) myself, there is always the main trail but animal trails and washes that look like trails, many single-track and narrow, are always present. It would be easy for inattentive newbies talking and snapping photos to start walking along one of these by mistake; 4) Kris's parents took a day trip and brought the necessary gear and supplies, but as we know based on the calls that were made on Kris and Lisanne's phones, that the two were out there for days with insufficient food and clothing. People have commented that they could have simply walked out. Seemed like Kris had gotten injured and Lisanne could not, or did not want, to leave her. With each passing day, the lack of food and exposure to the elements would have taken a toll on them mentally and physically. Other thoughts: Why did they take night shots of seemingly random things? Jungles come alive at night. I'd be doing the same thing if there were things moving around and making sounds in the darkness. Why did they call 112 (the equivalent of 911) in the Netherlands? My guess is because it was familiar to them. They had not been in Panama for very long after all and would have known that calling their homeland's emergency agency would have been more reliable than calling the hostel where they were staying. The Dutch responders would have immediately known to contact their parents to make them aware of the situation. Of course the rest of this tragic story raises more questions than answers and has many parts, but this is just my take about one of those parts.
